    think="Now I have all the information I need. Let me compile the review repo
rt.\n\n## Summary of findings:\n\n### ✅ Positive\n1. **Root cause fix**: Changi
ng `registerFactory` to `registerLazySingleton` and using `BlocProvider.value` c
orrectly fixes the issue where a new cubit was created on every rebuild, causing
`load()` to overwrite user input.\n2. **Widget test regression**: Added `drawer 
close and reopen preserves saved url` test.\n3. **Cubit already guarded**: `load
()` has `if (state.serverBaseUrl.isEmpty)` guard, which is good.\n4. **Documenta
tion updated**: `docs/modules/dev-tools.md` reflects the DI change.\n5. **BDD un
changed**: No behavior changes in BDD scenarios, so step definitions don't need 
updates.\n6. **Golden tests unaffected**: No visual changes.\n\n### ⚠️ Observatio
ns/Suggestions (non-blocking)\n1. **No Maestro E2E for dev-tools**: The project 
has no `.maestro/flows/dev-tools/` directory. Since dev-tools is debug-only and 
this is a bug fix, it's acceptable, but should be noted.\n2. **DevToolsWrapper d
ispose()**: The widget doesn't override `dispose()`. This is actually correct si
nce get_it owns the lazy singleton, but a comment might help clarity.\n\n### ❌ 
Blocking issues\nNone found.\n\nWait, I should double-check one more thing. In `
dev_tools_wrapper.dart`, the `_cubit` is obtained via `getIt<DevToolsCubit>()`. 
Since this is now a lazy singleton, it's the same instance throughout the app. B
ut what if `configureDependencies()` is called again? That would throw a `Assert
ionError` because get_it doesn't allow duplicate registrations by default. So th
at's fine.\n\nActually, let me reconsider whether there are any edge cases with 
the `BlocProvider.value` pattern. In `DevToolsWrapper`:\n```dart\nreturn BlocPro
vider.value(\n  value: _cubit,\n  child: Stack(...)\n);\n```\n\nIf `_cubit` emit
s a state change while the drawer is closed, widgets inside the drawer (like `Se
rverUrlTool`) are not in the tree, so they don't rebuild. When the drawer opens 
again, `ServerUrlTool` rebuilds with the current state. Since `ServerUrlTool` us
es `TextEditingController` initialized from `context.read<DevToolsCubit>().state
.serverBaseUrl` in `initState`, if the state changed while the drawer was closed
, the `TextEditingController` might be out of sync.\n\nWait, this is important! 
Let me re-read `ServerUrlTool.initState()`:\n\n```dart\n@override\nvoid initStat
e() {\n  super.initState();\n  _controller = TextEditingController(\n    text: c
ontext.read<DevToolsCubit>().state.serverBaseUrl,\n  );\n  _focusNode = FocusNod
e();\n}\n```\n\nAnd the `BlocListener`:\n```dart\nBlocListener<DevToolsCubit, De
vToolsState>(\n  listenWhen: (previous, current) =>\n      previous.serverBaseUr
l.isEmpty &&\n      current.serverBaseUrl.isNotEmpty &&\n      _controller.text.
isEmpty &&\n      !_focusNode.hasFocus,\n  listener: (context, state) {\n    _co
ntroller.text = state.serverBaseUrl;\n  },\n```\n\nSo when `ServerUrlTool` is fi
rst created (drawer opens), `_controller` is initialized with the current state.
The `BlocListener` only updates the controller when transitioning from empty to 
non-empty URL, and only if the controller is empty and not focused.\n\nNow, cons
ider the scenario with the bug fix:\n1. User opens drawer, enters URL `http://19
2.168.1.100:3000/api/v1`\n2. User saves, cubit state has `serverBaseUrl = http:/
/192.168.1.100:3000/api/v1`\n3. User closes drawer, `ServerUrlTool` is removed f
rom tree and disposed\n4. User reopens drawer, `ServerUrlTool` is recreated\n5. 
`initState` creates controller with text = `http://192.168.1.100:3000/api/v1` (f
rom cubit state)\n6. `BlocListener` won't trigger because state is already non-e
mpty\n\nThis works correctly! The URL is preserved.\n\nWhat about if `load()` co
mpletes after the user already entered text? That's handled by the `listenWhen` 
guard and the `load()` guard in the cubit.\n\nSo the fix is solid.\n\nOne final 
check: does the new widget test in `dev_tools_widget_test.dart` have any issues?
\n\n```dart\ntestWidgets('drawer close and reopen preserves saved url', (tester)
async {\n  await tester.pumpWidget(_buildWithCubit(cubit, const ServerUrlTool())
);\n  await tester.pump();\n\n  final textField = find.byType(TextField);\n  awa
it tester.enterText(textField, 'http://192.168.1.100:3000/api/v1');\n  await tes
ter.pumpAndSettle();\n\n  await tester.tap(find.widgetWithText(SwButton, '保存配
置'));\n  await tester.pumpAndSettle();\n\n  // Close drawer by removing ServerU
rlTool from tree (simulate Drawer closing)\n  await tester.pumpWidget(_buildWith
Cubit(cubit, const SizedBox.shrink()));\n  await tester.pumpAndSettle();\n\n  //
Reopen drawer with a new cubit that loads from repository\n  final newCubit = De
vToolsCubit(\n    repository: repository,\n    dioClient: dioClient,\n  );\n  aw
ait newCubit.load();\n\n  await tester.pumpWidget(\n    _buildWithCubit(newCubit
, const ServerUrlTool()),\n  );\n  await tester.pumpAndSettle();\n\n  expect(\n 
  tester.widget<TextField>(find.byType(TextField)).controller!.text,\n    'http:
//192.168.1.100:3000/api/v1',\n  );\n\n  await newCubit.close();\n});\n```\n\nWa
it, there's a subtle issue with this test. It creates a `newCubit` and loads fro
m repository. But with the actual fix, `DevToolsWrapper` would reuse the SAME cu
bit (singleton), not create a new one. This test simulates the OLD behavior (new
cubit on reopen) and verifies that the repository persistence works. \n\nBut sho
uldn't there be a test that verifies the ACTUAL fix - i.e., using the SAME cubit
instance? If we use the same cubit, the state is already `http://192.168.1.100:3
000/api/v1`, so `initState` of `ServerUrlTool` would initialize the controller w
ith that value.\n\nActually, the test as written is valid for verifying end-to-e
nd persistence (repository -> new cubit -> UI). But it doesn't specifically test
the singleton behavior. However, testing get_it singleton behavior in a widget t
est would require setting up get_it, which is typically not done in unit/widget 
tests. So this is acceptable.\n\nIs there any issue with the test closing `newCu
bit` at the end but `cubit` being closed in `tearDown`? No, that's fine.\n\nAlri
ght, I'm confident this PR should pass. Let me write the review report to `logs/
review-report-38.md`.\n\nOne more thing - I need to make sure the report format 
matches the requirements:\n- List issues with specific fix instructions (file pa
